            <p style="background-color:#835596;width:128px;color:white;text-align:center;height:40px;padding:10px; margin-top: 0px;margin-left:-1px;margin-left: 24px;">Collateral Swaps</p>

            <p style="font-family:calibri;padding-left: 25px;text-align: justify;font-size:16px;">
                In order to maintain HQLA for a bank’s desired level of risk appetite, and more importantly, to
                comply with Basel 3 norms, the bank can do one of the following:<br />
            </p>
            <div style="font-family:calibri;text-align: justify;margin: 2px 35px;font-size:16px;">
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        A minimum level of HQLAs, which, as the name indicates, will necessarily result in
                        lower than anticipated yields.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Sell its holding of lower quality assets and convert them to cash or cash equivalent; this may
                        not be feasible in times of stress and if the markets are against us.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Borrow cash from market participants; this may be expensive, and punitive as it is subjected
                        to a higher deposit run-off rates in the LCR and NSFR framework.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Issue long term debt or equity; this is time-consuming and liquidity essentially is a shortterm
                        phenomenon, and therefore may have catastrophic results.
                    </li>
                    
                </ol>
            </div><br />
            <div style="padding-left: 25px;text-align: justify;font-size:16px;font-family:calibri;margin-right: 38px;">
                A more elegant approach to manage this problem would be to swap lower quality assets held by the
                bank for a higher quality. Just as likely as the existence of an organisation that has a need for
                improving its liquidity position, there is the existence of organisations that have surplus liquidity and
                in need to increase their yields. This necessitates the need for a platform where such participants
                can come together, provide their portfolio of assets that they are willing to swap, and then, once a
                price is established, trade on the platform itself to construct such a swap.<br /><br />
                Thus, the bank can swap the lower quality assets for a higher quality, HQLA-compliant asset
                structure. Similarly, it can also swap a higher quality asset with a lower quality asset if its objective is
                to improve performance returns (i.e. Yield). The instrument to facilitate these swap activities is
                called a Collateral Swap. A collateral swap refers to the lending of liquid assets to another, in return
                for the receipt of less liquid collateral. The borrower of the liquid assets pays a fee to the lender to
                compensate for the risk of holding a less liquid asset.

            </div>
